b'' b'' b'anecedotal evidence is worthless. even doctors who have been using a drug' b'or treatment for years, and who swear it is effective, are often suprised' b'at the results of clinical trials. whether or not msg causes describable,' b'reportable, documentable symptoms should be pretty simple to discover.' b'' b'but it is quite a leap in logic to observe one situation where anecdotal' b'evidence led nowhere and therefore conclude that anecdotal evidence will' b"never lead anywhere. i'm sure somebody here can provide an example where" b'anecdotal evidence (and the interpretation of it) was upheld/verified by' b'follow-on rigorous clinical trials.' b'' b'' b'i tend to disagree- i think anecdotal evidence, provided there is a lot of it,' b'and it is fairly consistent, will is very important. first, it points to the' b'necessity of doing a study, and second, it at least says that the effects are' b"all psychological (or possibly allergy in this case). as i've pointed out" b'person\'s "make-believe" can easily be another person\'s reality...' b'' b'good point. there has been a tendency by some on this newsgroup to "circle' b'the wagons" to the viewpoint that anecdotal medical evidence is worthless' b'(maybe to counter the claims of those who are presenting anecdotal evidence' b'to support controversial subjects, such as the "yeast hypothesis"). but' b'evidence is evidence it requires a "jury" or a process to sort it out and' b'determine the truth from the junk. medicine must continue to strive to better' b'understand the workings of the body/mind for the purpose of alleviating' b'illness anecdotal evidence is just one piece of the puzzle; it is not' b'worthless. rather, it can help focus limited resources in the right direction.' b'' b'jon noring' b'' b'--' b'' b'charter member infj club.' b'' b"if you're dying to know what infj means, be brave, e-mail me, i'll send info." b'=============================================================================' b"| jkn inter